04253nam a22006615i 9780674038783DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20221977mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740387837 a10.4159/97806740387832doi  a(DE-B1597)590529  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF366 ǂb H67 1977eb 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a347.31 aHorwitz, Morton J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Transformation of American Law, 1780–1860 /cMorton J. Horwitz. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1977  a1 online resource (377 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Legal History00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tI. The Emergence of an Instrumental Conception of Law -- tII. The Transformation in the Conception of Property -- tIII. Subsidization of Economic Growth through the Legal System -- tIV. Competition and Economic Development -- tV. The Relation between the Bar and Commercial Interests -- tVI. The Triumph of Contract -- tVII. The Development of Commercial Law -- tVIII. The Rise of Legal Formalism -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tSTUDIES IN LEGAL HISTORY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a remarkable book based on prodigious research, Morton J. Horwitz offers a sweeping overview of the emergence of a national (and modern) legal system from English and colonial antecedents. He treats the evolution of the common law as intellectual history and also demonstrates how the shifting views of private law became a dynamic element in the economic growth of the United States. Horwitz's subtle and sophisticated explanation of societal change begins with the common law, which was intended to provide justice for all. The great breakpoint came after 1790 when the law was slowly transformed to favor economic growth and development. The courts spurred economic competition instead of circumscribing it. This new instrumental law flourished as the legal profession and the mercantile elite forged a mutually beneficial alliance to gain wealth and power. The evolving law of the early republic interacted with political philosophy, Horwitz shows. The doctrine of laissez-faire, long considered the cloak for competition, is here seen as a shield for the newly rich. By the 1840s the overarching reach of the doctrine prevented further distribution of wealth and protected entrenched classes by disallowing the courts very much power to intervene in economic life. This searching interpretation, which connects law and the courts to the real world, will engage historians in a new debate. For to view the law as an engine of vast economic transformation is to challenge in a stunning way previous interpretations of the eras of revolution and reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674038783zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674038783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674038783/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK